The data files are distributed as .csv.gz files instead of .csv files because the .csv.gz files are compressed data files using the gzip compression algorithm, which are smaller than the .csv files.

  1. Briefly describe what Bash commands zcat, zless, zmore, and zgrep do.

Answer: zcat is used to display the contents of a compressed file. zless is used to scroll through the contents of a compressed file one screen at a time, which allows us to read the whole content with navigation options. zmore is used to display the contents of a compressed file one screen at a time. zgrep is used to search for a pattern in a compressed file.

  1. To compress, or not to compress. Thatâs the question. Letâs focus on the big data file labevents.csv.gz. Compare compressed gz file size to the uncompressed file size. Compare the run times of zcat < ~/mimic/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l versus wc -l labevents.csv. Discuss the trade off between storage and speed for big data files. (Hint: gzip -dk < FILENAME.gz > ./FILENAME. Remember to delete the large labevents.csv file after the exercise.)

Answer:

##compressed
ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz
time zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l
ls: /Users/shu/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz: No such file or directory
bash: line 2: /Users/shu/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz: No such file or directory
       0

##uncompressed
gzip -d ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz
time wc -l < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv
gzip: can't stat: /Users/shu/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz (/Users/shu/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz.gz): No such file or directory
 118171368

real    0m20.253s
user    0m8.330s
sys 0m4.995s

As we can see, the compressed file size is less than 1G, and the uncompressed file size is 1.8G. The run time of zcat < ~/mimic/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l is 28s, and the run time of wc -l labevents.csv is 18s. The trade off between storage and speed for big data files is that the compressed file size is smaller than the uncompressed file size, but the run time of the compressed file is longer than the uncompressed file.

Q4. Whoâs popular in Price and Prejudice

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Among the four main characters in the book, Elizabeth, Jane, Lydia, and Darcy, your friend thinks that Darcy was the most mentioned. You, however, are certain it was Elizabeth. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.
wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt

Explain what wget -nc does. Do not put this text file pg42671.txt in Git. Complete the following loop to tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned using Linux commands.

Answer:

wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt
for char in Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy
do
  echo $char:
  grep -o -i "$char" pg42671.txt | wc -l
done

It is Elizabeth. wget -nc means that if the file already exists, it will not be downloaded again.

  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

and

echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

Answer: > means that the output will be written to the file, and if the file already exists, it will be overwritten. >> means that the output will be appended to the file, and if the file does not exist, it will be created.

  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:
#!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines
head -n "$2" "$1" | tail -n "$3"

Using chmod to make the file executable by the owner, and run

./middle.sh pg42671.txt 20 5

Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?

Answer: The output is the 5 lines from the 16th to 20th line of the file. "$1" means the pg42671.txt, "$2" means the first 20th line, and "$3" means last fifth line. We need the first line of the shell script because it tells the system which interpreter to use to execute the script.
